A seven-digit number (base 10) is squarish if it satisfies the following conditions: 
(i) it may contain at most one zero which is not in the first place; 
(ii) it is a perfect square; 
(iii) the first three digits, the next two digits, and the last two digits of the number are all perfect squares when considered as numbers. 
How many squarish numbers are there?
$\text{(A)} \ 0 \quad \text{(B)} \ 1 \quad \text{(C)} \ 2 \quad \text{(D)} \ 3 \quad \text{(E)} \ 4$

